'''Marko Arnautović''' ([[Serbian Cyrillic alphabet|Serbian Cyrillic]]: Марко Арнаутовић; born 19 April 1989) is an Austrian professional [[Football player|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] for [[Serbian SuperLiga]] club [[Red Star Belgrade]] and the [[Austria national football team|Austria national team]].

Arnautović began his career in his native country Austria playing in the youth teams for a number of clubs in the [[Vienna]] area before he signed a contract with Dutch club [[FC Twente|Twente]] in 2006. He impressed at [[De Grolsch Veste]] and after a fine [[2008–09 Eredivisie|2008–09]] season he joined Italian giants [[Inter Milan]] on loan, where he made only three appearances due to injury. He joined German side [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in June 2010 and became a regular member of the first-team. In September 2013, Arnautović joined English side [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], where he scored 26 goals in 145 appearances. He joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in July 2017 for a fee of £20 million and won the [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] award in his debut season. He scored 22 goals in 65 games for West Ham over two seasons before joining Shanghai SIPG (now [[Shanghai Port F.C.|Shanghai Port]]) for £22.4 million in July 2019. Arnautović returned to Europe to join Italian club Bologna in August 2021.

A full international with over 130 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for Austria since 2008,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ewige Einsatzliste |url=https://www.oefb.at/oefb/Teams/Maenner/Nationalteam/Statistik/Ewige-Einsatzliste |website=oefb.at |access-date=23 June 2023}}</ref> Arnautović is the [[Austria national football team#Most capped players|most-capped]] and [[Austria national football team#Top goalscorers|highest-scoring]] player in the history of the country's national team.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ewige Torschützen |url=https://www.oefb.at/oefb/Teams/Maenner/Nationalteam/Statistik/Ewige-Torschuetzen |website=oefb.at |access-date=23 June 2023}}</ref> He was part of the side that qualified for the [[UEFA European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016]], [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]], and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]], and was named [[Austrian Footballer of the Year]] in 2018.

==Early and personal life==
Marko Arnautović was born on 19 April 1989 in [[Vienna]],<ref name="Soccerway"/> to a [[Serbs|Serbian]] father and an Austrian mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austriantimes.at/index.php?id=13493 |title=Ivanschitz left off squad for Serbia clash |access-date=8 August 2009 |work=Austrian Times |date=26 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.austriantimes.at/index.php?id=13493 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 
Arnautović is a [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodox Christian]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Marko Arnautović sa tri prsta na grudima tokom intoniranja "Bože pravde"!|date=10 October 2016|publisher=[[Radio Television of Serbia]]|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/sport/sr/story/36/fudbal/2483174/marko-arnautovic-sa-tri-prsta-na-grudima-tokom-intoniranja-boze-pravde.html}}</ref> He is married to Sarah ({{née|Lizakowski}}), and together they have two daughters, Emilia and Alicia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Balczuweit |first=Markus |title=So lief seine Traumhochzeit |trans-title=This was his dream wedding |url=http://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/marko-arnautovic/so-lief-seine-traumhochzeit-24560526.bild.html |work=[[Bild]] |date=8 June 2012 |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/marko-arnautovic/so-lief-seine-traumhochzeit-24560526.bild.html|archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fußballer Marko Arnautovic zeigt erstmals sein Baby |trans-title=Football player Marko Arnautovic shows his baby for the first time |date=8 September 2012 |url=http://www.krone.at/Stars-Society/Fussballer_Marko_Arnautovic_zeigt_erstmals_sein_Baby-Liebevoller_Vater-Story-333324 |publisher=Krone.at|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.krone.at/Stars-Society/Fussballer_Marko_Arnautovic_zeigt_erstmals_sein_Baby-Liebevoller_Vater-Story-333324 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During his time spent in Italy and Germany, Arnautović developed a reputation with the media as "the bad boy of Austrian football". Speaking on the matter in October 2013, he admitted he was "not an angel" but insisted that the birth of his daughter had made him "grow up".<ref>{{cite news|last=Percy |first=John |title=Stoke City's Marko Arnautovic, friend of Mario Balotelli, admits he is 'not an angel' but insists he has grown up |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 October 2013 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/stoke-city/10387084/Stoke-Citys-Marko-Arnautovic-friend-of-Mario-Balotelli-admits-he-is-not-an-angel-but-insists-he-has-grown-up.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/stoke-city/10387084/Stoke-Citys-Marko-Arnautovic-friend-of-Mario-Balotelli-admits-he-is-not-an-angel-but-insists-he-has-grown-up.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is fluent in [[Serbian language|Serbian]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cRsHdcueI-s</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Arnautović began his career with his brother Danijel at [[FAC Team für Wien|Floridsdorfer AC]]. In 1998, he joined [[FK Austria Wien]] but behaviour issues saw him change clubs regularly as in the next six years he played for [[First Vienna FC|First Vienna FC 1894]], a second spell at FK Austria Wien, and [[SK Rapid Wien]] before he returned to Floridsdorfer AC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria's wayward son|url=http://espnfc.com/columns/story/_/id/897635/andy-brassell-on-austria-starlet-marko-arnautovic?cc=5739|publisher=[[ESPN]] | date = 23 March 2011 | access-date = 4 May 2014 | first = Andy | last = Brassell}}</ref> Despite this he was scouted by Dutch club [[FC Twente]] who signed him in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Werder verstärkt sich mit Arnautovic|trans-title=Werder reinforced with Arnautovic|language=de|date=4 June 2010|access-date=4 June 2010|publisher=[[Deutsche Fußball Liga|DFL]]|url=http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/2009/werder-verstaerkt-sich-mit-arnautovic_0000154935.php|archive-date=4 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504223046/http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/2009/werder-verstaerkt-sich-mit-arnautovic_0000154935.php|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Twente===
Arnautović scored 22 goals in 24 matches for the Under-19 FC Twente in the 2007–08 season, helping them win the youth championship. He then played for [[Jong FC Twente]] between 2006 and 2008, appearing in 32 matches and scoring 27 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://derstandard.at/1246543874097/Portraet-In-drei-Jahren-vom-Kaefig-nach-San-Siro|title=In drei Jahren vom "Käfig" nach San Siro|language= de |publisher=[[Der Standard]]|date=5 August 2009 | access-date = 4 May 2014}}</ref> Arnautović made his professional debut for [[FC Twente]] in the 2006–07 season as a substitute for [[Kennedy Bakircioglu]] against [[PSV Eindhoven]] in April 2007. In July 2008, he extended his contract with Twente despite interest from Dutch giant [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[De Telegraaf]] |language=nl |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/1488443/__Arnautovic_blijft_bij_Twente__.html |title=Arnautovic blijft bij Twente |trans-title=Arnautovic stays with Twente |access-date=14 June 2010 |date=14 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/1488443/__Arnautovic_blijft_bij_Twente__.html?p=6%2C1 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

He made 16 appearances in [[2007–08 Eredivisie|2007–08]] as Twente finished in fourth position and qualified for the [[UEFA Champions League]]. In the [[2008–09 Eredivisie|2008–09]] season Arnautović scored 14 goals in 41 matches as Twente finished 2nd in the [[Eredivisie]] and reached the knock out phase of the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Offside (magazine)|The Offside]] |title=Name To Remember: Marko Arnautovic |url=http://www.theoffside.com/world-football/name-to-remember-marko-arnautovic.html |access-date=3 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.theoffside.com/world-football/name-to-remember-marko-arnautovic.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2009 after a league match against [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]], one of Twente opponents, [[Ibrahim Kargbo]], accused Arnautović of racially abusing him. An investigation by the [[KNVB|Dutch Football Association]] found no evidence against him, and the case was dismissed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arnautovic innocent of racism |url=http://austriantimes.at/?id=11996-newentry |work=Austrian Times |access-date=3 September 2013 |date=24 March 2009 |first=Thomas |last=Hochwarter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://austriantimes.at/?id=11996-newentry |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

====Loan to Inter Milan====
On 4 August 2009, it was said that Arnautović was on the verge of a move to Italian giants [[Inter Milan]]. The deal had been largely held up due to a stress fracture in Arnautović's right foot, leading to a re-negotiation of the deal between the clubs.<ref>{{cite web|date=6 August 2009 |access-date=6 August 2009 |url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/serie-a/news/detail/item302920/Arnautovic-set-for-Inter-switch |title=Arnautovic set for inter switch |publisher=[[ESPN Star]] |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729164353/http://www.espnstar.com/football/serie-a/news/detail/item302920/Arnautovic-set-for-Inter-switch |archive-date=29 July 2012 |url-status=usurped }}</ref> On 6 August, it was announced by Twente that the details for the loan had been finalised, Arnautović would join Inter on loan for the season. The deal was said to become permanent if he was to play a set number of matches. If the deal did not become permanent the player would return to Twente on a pre-agreed contract of two years, with an option to extend the contract for a third year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fctwente.com/en/news/index.php?item=8787 |title=Arnautovic signs for Inter |publisher=[[FC Twente]] |access-date=6 August 2009 |date=6 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.fctwente.com/en/news/index.php?item=8787 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his unofficial debut for Inter in a friendly match on 5 September 2009 against Swiss team, [[FC Lugano|Lugano]], the final score was 3–3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inter.theoffside.com/international-duty/inter-3-3-lugano.html |title=Inter 3–3 Lugano |publisher=The Offside |access-date=25 September 2009 |date=5 September 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://inter.theoffside.com/international-duty/inter-3-3-lugano.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

He made his league debut in a 1–0 away victory against [[A.C. Chievo Verona|Chievo]] on 6 January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chievo-Inter: 0–1, Winter Champions |url=http://www.inter.it/it/news/46908 |language=it |work=Inter |date=6 January 2010 |access-date=3 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.inter.it/it/news/46908 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played in their next match against [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] coming on as a substitute at half time for the injured [[Dejan Stanković]] and helped Inter to win the match 4–3.<ref>{{cite web|title=L'evoluzione di Arnautovic: Mou oggi si fida di lui |trans-title=The evolution of Arnautovic: Mou now trusts him |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/inter/?action=read&idnet=ZmNpbnRlcm5ld3MuaXQtMTI1OTk |work=tuttomercatoweb.com |access-date=3 September 2013 |date=10 January 2010 |language=it |first=Fabio |last=Costantino |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/inter/?action=read&idnet=ZmNpbnRlcm5ld3MuaXQtMTI1OTk |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played one more match for Inter against [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] on 24 April 2010. At the end of the season Inter decided against turning his loan into a permanent move with manager [[José Mourinho]] stating that Arnautović "is a fantastic person but has the attitude of a child".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/de/news/843/serie-a/2010/01/05/1727328/mourinho-arnautovic-hat-die-einstellung-eines-kindes |title=Mourinho: "Arnautovic hat die Einstellung eines Kindes" |publisher=Goal.com |language=de |date=5 January 2010 |access-date=11 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.goal.com/de/news/843/serie-a/2010/01/05/1727328/mourinho-arnautovic-hat-die-einstellung-eines-kindes |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Werder Bremen===
[[File:Marko Arnautovic 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Arnautović training with [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in 2010]]

On 4 June 2010, [[Bundesliga]] club [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] confirmed that they had signed Arnautović from Twente on a four-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.werder.de/de/profis/news/13902.php|title=Perfekt: Stürmer Arnautovic wird Werderaner|trans-title=Done deal: Forward Arnautovic comes to Werder|access-date=14 June 2010|date=4 June 2010|language=de|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504230230/http://www.werder.de/de/profis/news/13902.php|archive-date=4 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fctwente.nl/blog/2010/06/arnautovic-naar-werder-bremen/|title=Arnautovic naar Werder Bremen|date=4 June 2010|access-date=4 May 2014|work=FC Twente|language=nl|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505003058/http://www.fctwente.nl/blog/2010/06/arnautovic-naar-werder-bremen/|archive-date=5 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Before he had played a match for Bremen he irked their captain [[Torsten Frings]] who branded him as "arrogant".<ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesliga – Frings attacks 'arrogant' Arnautovic |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/05082010/58/bundesliga-frings-attacks-arrogant-arnautovic.html |work=[[Eurosport]] |access-date=6 September 2013 |date=5 August 2010 |language=de |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/05082010/58/bundesliga-frings-attacks-arrogant-arnautovic.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his Bundesliga debut on 21 August 2010 in a 4–1 defeat against [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hoffenheim 4–1 Werder Bremen |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/08/21/germany/bundesliga/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-ev/sv-werder-bremen/958439/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=6 September 2013 |date=21 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821191632/http://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2010/08/21/germany/bundesliga/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-ev/sv-werder-bremen/958439/ |archive-date=21 August 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Arnautović scored twice against [[1. FC Köln]] on 28 August 2010, his first goals for Bremen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Werder Bremen 4–2 Koln |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/08/28/germany/bundesliga/sv-werder-bremen/1-fc-koln/958448/ |website=Soccerway |date=28 August 2010 |access-date=6 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2010/08/28/germany/bundesliga/sv-werder-bremen/1-fc-koln/958448/ |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He ended the [[2010–11 Bundesliga|2010–11]] season at the [[Weserstadion]] with five goals in 34 appearances as Bremen finished in 13th position and he also played in the [[2010–11 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], scoring two goals in the competition against his former clubs, Twente and Inter Milano.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/01ea-0e75e18d9db2-c2bc9cce5de1-1000--arnautovic-earns-bremen-a-point-at-twente/ |title=Arnautović earns Bremen a point at Twente |publisher=UEFA |date=20 October 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/01ec-0ea1c4cb575f-19a786b6bff0-1000--final-bremen-flourish-flattens-inter/ |title=Final Bremen flourish flattens Inter |publisher=UEFA |date=7 December 2010 }}</ref> In [[2011–12 SV Werder Bremen season|2011–12]], he scored six goals in 20 appearances as Bremen finished in ninth position in the Bundesliga.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} In March 2012, he was ruled out for two months with a knee ligament injury he suffered whilst playing with his dog.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesliga – Arnautovic tears ligament in game with dog |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/08032012/58/bundesliga-arnautovic-tears-ligament-game-dog.html |work=Eurosport |date=8 March 2013 |access-date=4 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/08032012/58/bundesliga-arnautovic-tears-ligament-game-dog.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In [[2012–13 Bundesliga|2012–13]], Arnautović played in 27 matches and scored five goals which included a hat-trick on 2 December 2012 away at [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]], including an impressive free kick, as Bremen won 4–1.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://espnfc.com/us/en/report/346277/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5901|title=TSG Hoffenheim 1–4 Werder Bremen|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|date=2 December 2012 | access-date = 4 May 2014}}</ref> In April 2013, Arnautović and his Bremen teammate [[Eljero Elia]] were caught speeding and were both suspended by the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesliga: Marko Arnautovic keen to put a 'big mistake' behind him |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11888/8813229/bundesliga-marko-arnautovic-keen-to-put-a-big-mistake-behind-him |work=Sky Sports |access-date=3 September 2013 |date=8 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11888/8813229/bundesliga-marko-arnautovic-keen-to-put-a-big-mistake-behind-him |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Stoke City===
On 2 September 2013, Arnautović joined [[Premier League]] side [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on a four-year contract for a fee of £2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marko Arnautovic: Stoke City sign Austria winger on four-year deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23925792 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=2 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23925792 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcoming Marko |url=http://www.stokecityfc.com/news/article/welcoming-marko-1029278.aspx |publisher=Stoke City F.C |date=2 September 2013 |access-date=2 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.stokecityfc.com/news/article/welcoming-marko-1029278.aspx |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was assigned the number 10 shirt by manager [[Mark Hughes]] who also described his signing as a coup—"People will very quickly see what an outstanding talent he is. In terms of his power and his pace, which is something I think we need in the squad, he ticks all the boxes. Technically he's excellent and I'm really looking forward to working with him. I think it's quite a coup to get him here. It made sense to us and made sense to him that this is the right club for him. He's got a real desire to make an impression."<ref>{{cite web|title=New signings receive squad numbers |url=http://www.stoke.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=331452 |work=Vital Stoke |access-date=6 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.stoke.vitalfootball.co.uk/article.asp?a=331452 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Marko Arnautovic on a mission to make an impact | url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/story-19761208-detail/story.html | newspaper=Stoke Sentinel |date=6 September 2013 |access-date=6 September 2013 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Arnautović made his Stoke debut twelve days later in a 0–0 draw against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at the [[Britannia Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke 0–0 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23999231 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2013 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |access-date=27 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23999231 |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After spending a month at the club, manager Hughes stated that Arnautović had adapted well to English football after being given a free-role in the side.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mark Hughes: Marko Arnautovic has been great at Stoke City |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Mark-Hughes-Marko-Arnautovic-great-Stoke-City/story-19885257-detail/story.html |newspaper=Stoke Sentinel |access-date=14 October 2013 |date=4 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Mark-Hughes-Marko-Arnautovic-great-Stoke-City/story-19885257-detail/story.html |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Stoke City: Why Marko Arnautovic loves his 'Freigeists' role |newspaper=Stoke Sentinel |access-date=14 October 2013 |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-loves-Freigeists-role/story-19908326-detail/story.html |first=Martin |last=Spinks |date=9 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319023532/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-loves-Freigeists-role/story-19908326-detail/story.html |archive-date=19 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 26 October, he scored his first goal for Stoke, a 25-yard free-kick in a 3–2 defeat against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester United 3–2 Stoke City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24591160 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 October 2013 |access-date=26 October 2013 |first=Chris |last=Bevan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026194204/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24591160 |archive-date=26 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Arnautović ended his first season in England with five goals in 35 appearances, and the team finished in ninth position in the Premier League.<ref name="2013/14"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Get used to clubs sniffing round Marko Arnautovic and Co|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-used-clubs-sniffing-round-Marko/story-21105560-detail/story.html?|newspaper=Stoke Sentinel|date=17 May 2014|access-date=17 May 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517121817/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-used-clubs-sniffing-round-Marko/story-21105560-detail/story.html|archive-date=17 May 2014}}</ref>

After making little impact in the first few matches of the [[2014–15 Stoke City F.C. season|2014–15 season]], Arnautović lost his place in the side.<ref>{{cite web | title=Marko Arnautovic reveals talks with Mark Hughes about playing time | url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-reveals-talks-Mark/story-24529154-detail/story.html| newspaper=Stoke Sentinel | date=14 November 2014 | access-date=8 November 2015 | first=Pete | last = Smith | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150930005806/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-reveals-talks-Mark/story-24529154-detail/story.html | archive-date = 30 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He regained his form towards the end of the campaign and returned to a regular place.<ref>{{cite web | title=Marko Arnautovic insists his future lies at the Britannia Stadium | url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-insists-future-lies/story-26371707-detail/story.html | newspaper=Stoke Sentinel | date=22 April 2015 | access-date=8 November 2015 | first=Rich | last=Sharpe | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150721110105/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Marko-Arnautovic-insists-future-lies/story-26371707-detail/story.html | archive-date = 21 July 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He scored once in 29 league appearances over the campaign: a 95th-minute equaliser against West Ham United on 11 April 2015, having earlier in the match had two goals disallowed for offside.<ref>{{cite web|title=West Ham United 1–1 Stoke City | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32179965 | publisher=BBC Sport | date=11 April 2015 | access-date=8 November 2015 | first=Tim | last=Oscroft}}</ref> He played 35 times in 2014–15 season as Stoke finished in ninth position.<ref name="2014/15"/>

Arnautović's first appearance of the [[2015–16 Stoke City F.C. season|2015–16 season]] came in a 2–2 draw with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]] on 15 August, scoring the team's first goal as they came back from 2–0 down.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33832169 | title=Tottenham Hotspur 2–2 Stoke City |date=15 August 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=8 November 2015 | first=Timothy | last=Abraham}}</ref> He scored the only goal of Stoke's victory over champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 7 November,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/34686371 | title=Stoke City 1–0 Chelsea | date=7 November 2015 | publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=8 November 2015 | first=Phil | last=McNulty}}</ref> and both goals against Manchester City on 5 December in a 2–0 home victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/34951742 | title=Stoke City 2–0 Manchester City | date=5 December 2015 | publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=5 December 2015 | first=Chris | last=Osborne}}</ref> On 28 December, Arnautović won a last-minute [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]] when he was fouled by [[John Stones]], and sent it past goalkeeper [[Tim Howard]] to win the match 4–3.<ref>{{cite news| last=Reddy| first=Luke |title=Everton 3–4 Stoke City | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35148469 | access-date=29 December 2015 | publisher=BBC Sport | date=28 December 2015}}</ref> He scored the only goal of the League Cup semi-final second leg against Liverpool on 26 January 2016, forcing a [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] which his team eventually lost.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ogden|first1=Marc|title=Liverpool vs Stoke match report: Simon Mignolet sends Reds to Wembley after Marc Muniesa misses in sudden death|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/liverpool-vs-stoke-match-report-simon-mignolet-sends-reds-to-wembley-after-marc-muniesa-misses-in-a6835741.html|access-date=27 January 2016|work=The Independent|date=26 January 2016}}</ref> Arnautović went on to play 40 times for Stoke in 2015–16, finishing as the top scorer with 12 goals as the Potters again finished in ninth position.<ref name="2015/16"/>

Arnautović signed a new four-year contract with Stoke in July 2016, keeping him contracted with the Potters until the summer of 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Charles|first1=Andy|title=Stoke City's Marko Arnautovic signs new four-year contract|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11701/10514311/stoke-citys-marko-arnautovic-signs-new-four-year-contract?|website=Sky Sports|access-date=27 July 2016}}</ref> Arnautović made 35 appearances in [[2016–17 Stoke City F.C. season|2016–17]], as Stoke finished in 13th position.<ref name="2016/17"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke 2016/17 Premier League season review|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11701/10887143/stoke-201617-premier-league-season-review|website=Sky Sports|access-date=22 May 2017}}</ref> He scored seven goals including braces against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Sunderland 1–3 Stoke City |date=13 January 2017 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38539374 | publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=29 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Stoke City 2–0 Middlesbrough | date=3 March 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39086670 | publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=29 May 2017}}</ref>

Arnautović's future at Stoke was cast in doubt prior to the start of the [[2017–18 Stoke City F.C. season|2017–18]] season after he submitted a transfer request.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marko Arnautovic: Stoke reject bid from West Ham for Austria forward |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40588584 |publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 July 2017 |access-date=23 July 2017}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
[[File:Marko Arnautović West Ham.jpg|thumb|upright|Arnautović training with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2018]]

On 22 July 2017, Arnautović signed for fellow Premier League team [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on a five-year contract for a club record £20&nbsp;million fee, which could rise to £25&nbsp;million with add-ons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marko Arnautovic: West Ham sign Stoke City and Austria forward for £20m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40648924 |publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 July 2017 |access-date=23 July 2017}}</ref>

He made his debut on 13 August, playing the full 90 minutes of a 4–0 loss to Manchester United at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burt|first1=Jason|title=Manchester United 4 West Ham 0: Romelu Lukaku scores two as Jose Mourinho's team start the season in style|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/08/13/manchester-united-vs-west-ham-premier-league-watch-live-score/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/08/13/manchester-united-vs-west-ham-premier-league-watch-live-score/ |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=9 December 2017|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 August 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In his next game six days later, he was sent off after 33 minutes for elbowing Southampton's [[Jack Stephens (footballer)|Jack Stephens]] in a 3–2 away loss.<ref name="redCard">{{cite news|last1=Warrington|first1=Declan|title=Slaven Bilic hails 'spirit' of 10-man West Ham as Marko Arnautovic apologises to fans for Southampton red card|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/southampton-west-ham-slaven-bilic-hails-spirit-marko-arnautovic-apology-fans-red-card-a3615666.html|access-date=9 December 2017|work=London Evening Standard|date=20 August 2017}}</ref>

In November, new manager [[David Moyes]] said that Arnautović had to work harder and be more of a team player or be dropped.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steinberg|first1=Jacob|title=David Moyes urges Marko Arnautovic to up his game for West Ham|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/17/david-moyes-marko-arnautovic-west-ham|access-date=9 December 2017|work=The Guardian|date=17 November 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 9 December, the only one of a win over reigning champions Chelsea at the [[London Stadium]], in what was Moyes' first victory as West Ham manager.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ames|first1=Nick|title=West Ham's Marko Arnautovic sinks Chelsea to delight of David Moyes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/dec/09/west-ham-united-chelsea-premier-league-match-report|access-date=9 December 2017|work=The Observer|date=9 December 2017}}</ref> He followed this with a goal in his first return to the [[Bet365 Stadium]] in a 0–3 win against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 16 December.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Stoke City 0–3 West Ham United | publisher=BBC Sport | date=16 December 2017 | access-date=16 December 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42290587}}</ref> Following his conversion from a winger to a centre-forward at West Ham,<ref>{{cite news |title=Marko Arnautovic: How David Moyes helped one of the Premier League's great enigmas turn his latest corner|last1=Liew|first1=Jonathan|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/marko-arnautovic-profile-west-ham-stoke-preview-team-news-david-moyes-latest-jonathan-liew-a8305716.html|publisher=Independent|date=16 April 2018|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref> Arnautović scored 11 Premier League goals in his first season at the club; his goal against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on the final day of the campaign making him the first West Ham player to reach that figure since [[Bobby Zamora]] in [[2006–07 West Ham United F.C. season|2006–07]].<ref>{{Cite web | title=West Ham United 3–1 Everton | publisher=BBC Sport | date=13 May 2018 | access-date=15 May 2018 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44020200}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=OptaJoe |number=995686425663279104 |date=13 May 2018 |title=11 – Marko Arnautovic has scored 11 Premier League goals this season, the most by a West Ham player in a single top-flight campaign since Bobby Zamora in 2006–07 (also 11). Legs. }}</ref> In April 2018, he was named as [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] for the [[2017–18 West Ham United F.C. season|2017–18 season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/april/25-april/arnautovic-crowned-betway-hammer-year | title=Arnautovic crowned Betway Hammer of the Year | publisher=West Ham United F.C. | date=25 April 2018 | access-date=26 April 2018}}</ref>

In January 2019, he was the subject of a £35&nbsp;million transfer offer from a Chinese club, believed to be [[Shanghai SIPG F.C.|Shanghai SIPG]], which his agent and brother, Danijel, said Arnautović wanted West Ham to accept.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46830073 | title=Marko Arnautovic: West Ham forward 'wants club to accept £35m Chinese bid' | publisher=BBC Sport | date=10 January 2019 | access-date=11 January 2019}}</ref> Despite this, on 26 January, Arnautović committed himself to West Ham by signing a contract extension of unspecified length.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47018041 | title=Marko Arnautovic: West Ham striker signs contract extension with Premier League club | publisher=BBC Sport | date = 26 January 2019 | access-date = 27 January 2019}}</ref> He also received a 20% increase raising his weekly wage to £120,000. A £40&nbsp;million release clause was also added to his contract.<ref name=sipg>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11685/11757712/marko-arnautovic-to-shanghai-sipg-west-ham-forward-passes-medical-ahead-of-china-move|title=Marko Arnautovic to Shanghai SIPG: West Ham forward passes medical ahead of China move|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Arnautović finished the 2018–19 season as West Ham's leading goal scorer, with 11 goals.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football | title=West Ham United Top Scorers | publisher=BBC Sport | access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, West Ham rejected an offer of £19.7&nbsp;million from a Chinese club as Arnautović said he wanted to leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48839607|title=Marko Arnautovic: West Ham reject £19.7m bid for striker|date=2 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019|first=Simon|last=Stone}}</ref>

===Shanghai Port===
On 7 July 2019, Arnautović signed for Shanghai SIPG (later rebranded as [[Shanghai Port F.C.|Shanghai Port]]) for a fee of £22.4&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48876616 | title=Marko Arnautovic: West Ham forward completes Shanghai SIPG move | publisher=BBC Sport | first=Simon | last=Stone | date=7 July 2019 | access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> He scored on his debut two weeks later, a 2–2 draw at [[Chongqing Dangdai Lifan F.C.|Chongqing Dangdai Lifan]] in the [[Chinese Super League]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Church |first1=Michael |title=Marko Arnautovic scores on Shanghai SIPG debut after West Ham exit |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/marko-arnautovic-scores-on-shanghai-sipg-debut-after-west-ham-exit-a4194966.html |access-date=7 November 2019 |work=Evening Standard |date=21 July 2019}}</ref>

===Bologna===
On 1 August 2021, Arnautović signed a two-year deal with Serie A side [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Marko Arnautovic at Bologna |url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/marko-arnautovic-at-bologna/ |access-date=1 August 2021 |work=Bologna F.C. 1909 |date=1 August 2021 }}</ref> On 15 August, Arnautović made his debut for Bologna, in a 5–4 defeat against [[Ternana Calcio|Ternana]] in the first round of the [[2021–22 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], scoring a goal in the 56th minute.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Clamoroso al Dall'Ara: la Ternana batte 4-5 il Bologna. Rossoblù fuori dalla Coppa Italia - TUTTOmercatoWEB.com|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/clamoroso-al-dall-ara-la-ternana-batte-4-5-il-bologna-rossoblu-fuori-dalla-coppa-italia-1571562|access-date=16 August 2021|website=www.tuttomercatoweb.com|language=it}}</ref>

====Second loan to Inter Milan====
[[File:FC Salzburg gegen Inter Mailand (UEFA Championsleague 2023-11-08) 47.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Arnautovic in 2023]]
On 16 August 2023, Arnautović for the second time in his career joined Inter Milan on loan, returning to the club after 13 years.<ref>{{cite news |title= Marko Arnautovic joins Inter |url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/marko-arnautovic-joins-inter |access-date=16 August 2023 |work=Inter Milan |date=16 August 2023 }}</ref> He chose 8 as his shirt number, alluding to [[Zlatan Ibrahimović]], who wore this number from 2006 to 2009 while playing for the club.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-17 |title=FOTO − Arnautovic "sfida" Ibrahimovic: il riferimento all'ex Inter! |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/foto-arnautovic-sfida-ibrahimovic-il-riferimento-allex-inter-38058598 |access-date=2024-08-17 |website=OneFootball |language=en}}</ref> On 29 November, he netted his first Champions League goal with Inter in a 3–3 away draw with [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/687614 |title=Inter complete stunning comeback to snatch draw with Benfica |publisher=ESPN |date=30 November 2023 }}</ref> which was the longest time any player had scored since previously scoring in the competition, after 12 years and 357 days from his last goal in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailysports.net/news/the-inter-milan-forward-scored-his-first-goal-in-the-uefa-champions-league-since-2010/ |title=The Inter Milan forward scored his first goal in the UEFA Champions League since 2010 |publisher=Dailysports |date=30 November 2023 }}</ref> On 20 February 2024, he scored the only goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Atlético Madrid]] in the first leg of the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/feb/20/marko-arnautovic-gives-inter-slim-last-16-lead-over-atletico-madrid |title=Marko Arnautovic gives Inter slim last-16 lead over Atlético Madrid |work=The Guardian |date=20 February 2024 }}</ref>

===Permanent move to Inter===
Arnautovic made a permanent move to Inter in the [[2024–25 Inter Milan season|2024–25 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.calcioefinanza.it/2024/10/28/inter-costo-giocatori-2023-2024-arnautovic-frattesi-zielinski/|title=Inter, il mercato a bilancio: da Frattesi a Zielinski e Arnautovic, le cifre ufficiali degli acquisti|trans-title=Inter, the market on balance: from Frattesi to Zielinski and Arnautovic, the official figures of the purchases|first=Matteo|last=Spaziante|date=28 October 2024|work=Calcio e Finanza|accessdate=7 March 2025|language=it}}</ref> During the 2024–25 season, Marko Arnautović featured primarily as a backup striker for Inter Milan, making 18 Serie A appearances and scoring 4 goals with 2 assists in 542 minutes of play. Across all competitions, he contributed 9 goals and 1 assist in 896 minutes, averaging a goal contribution every 76 minutes. Despite limited starts behind Lautaro Martínez and Marcus Thuram, Arnautović delivered decisive performances, including a goal and an assist in a league win over Cagliari and a volleyed strike in the Coppa Italia quarter-final against Lazio. While occasionally criticized for missed chances, such as in the UEFA Champions League match against Monaco, his physical presence, experience, and efficiency off the bench were praised by Italian media and former players like Alessandro Altobelli, solidifying his role as a reliable impact player throughout the season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=The official website for European football |url=https://www.uefa.com/errors/ |access-date=2025-07-20 |website=UEFA.com |language=en}}</ref>

=== Red Star Belgrade ===
In July 2025, Arnautović signed a two-year contract with [[Red Star Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Official : Arnautovic joins Red Star Belgrade as free agent at age 36 | website=Football Italia | date=21 July 2025 | url=https://football-italia.net/official-arnautovic-joins-red-star-belgrade/ | access-date=22 July 2025}}</ref> Arnautovic revealed in the press conference which unveiled his signing that the transfer fulfilled a promise to his Bologna manager and friend, [[Siniša Mihajlović]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Arnautovic in tears remembering Mihajlovic love for Red Star Belgrade |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/arnautovic-tears-remembering-mihajlovic-love-130000081.html |website=yahoo! sports |access-date=8 September 2025}}</ref> Mihajlović won the [[1991 European Cup Final]] and [[FIFA Intercontinental Cup|Intercontinental Cup]] while at Red Star, and died of [[leukaemia]] in 2022.

==International career==
[[File:20130814 AT-GR Marko Arnautovic 2497.jpg|thumb|upright|Arnautović playing for [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in 2013]]

=== Youth ===
Arnautović played with the Austrian under-19 side in the [[2007 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] where he was sent-off in their second match and failed to make it out of the group stage. He made four appearances in total at under-19 level.<ref name=youthstats>{{cite web|title=M. Arnautovic|url=https://www.besoccer.com/player/m-arnautovic-1659|website=www.besoccer.com|access-date=7 August 2022}}</ref> He scored three goals in five matches for the [[Austria national under-21 football team|Austria under-21 team]].<ref name=youthstats/> After scoring a free-kick in an under-21 game against Denmark in March 2010, Arnautović earned praise from manager [[Andreas Herzog]] who described him as the best Austrian footballer of the last 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Herzog über Arnautovic: "Bester Spieler der letzten 30 Jahre" |trans-title=Herzog about Arnautovic: "Best player of the past 30 years" |url=http://derstandard.at/1267132294666/Herzog-ueber-Arnautovic-Bester-Spieler-der-letzten-30-Jahre |work=Der Standard |language=de |date=4 March 2010 |access-date=5 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://derstandard.at/1267132294666/Herzog-ueber-Arnautovic-Bester-Spieler-der-letzten-30-Jahre |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

=== Senior ===
Arnautović played his first match for the Austria national senior team on 11 October 2008, against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]]. He scored his first goals for Austria in a 3–0 win over [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] on 8 October 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria 3–0 Azerbaijan |url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/299356/report.html?soccernet=true |publisher=[[ESPN]] |access-date=5 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201194141/http://espnfc.com/en/report/299356/report.html?soccernet=true |archive-date=1 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Arnautović started in all ten of Austria's matches during their successful [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] campaign, scoring in a win over [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] and both fixtures against neighbours [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Austria-boss-tells-Marko-Arnautovic/story-27985950-detail/story.html | title=Stoke City: Austria boss tells Marko Arnautovic 'Stoke is not your last stop'| date=14 October 2015 | newspaper=Stoke Sentinel | access-date=8 November 2015|first=Pete|last=Smith|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117011749/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Austria-boss-tells-Marko-Arnautovic/story-27985950-detail/story.html|archive-date=17 November 2015}}</ref> On 31 May 2016, he was selected in the Austrian squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Der EURO Kader steht |url=http://www.oefb.at/valentino-lazaro-muss-das-oefbteam-news25719 |publisher=[[Austrian Football Association]] |language=de |access-date=31 May 2016 |archive-date=31 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531222705/http://www.oefb.at/valentino-lazaro-muss-das-oefbteam-news25719 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Arnautović started all but one of Austria's [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group D|qualification matches]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], only missing the game against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] through suspension.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Republic of Ireland v Austria Match Report, 11/06/2017, WC Qualification Europe | first=Patric | last=Ridge | website=Goal.com | date=11 June 2017 | access-date=4 July 2018 | url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/republic-of-ireland-v-austria/7t31kmcv9nz066th7snrc66zt}}</ref> He scored four goals in the 10 games, but Austria's fourth-place finish would not be enough for qualification.<ref>{{Cite web | title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia – Qualifiers – Europe | publisher=FIFA | access-date=4 July 2018 | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/group=276493/index.html| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906134420/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/group=276493/index.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=6 September 2015}}</ref>

On 24 May 2021, he was called up for the [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oefb.at/oefb/News/Franco-Foda-fixiert-26-Spieler-umfassenden-EURO-Kader |title=Franco Foda fixiert 26 Spieler umfassenden EURO-Kader |trans-title=Franco Foda fixes the 26-player Euro squad |work=[[Austrian Football Association]] |date=24 May 2021 |access-date=24 May 2021 |language=de}}</ref> On 13 June, Arnautović scored the third goal for Austria during [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group C#Austria vs North Macedonia|the first game of Group C]] against [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=UEFA.com|title=Austria-North Macedonia|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024442/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317164448/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024442/|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 March 2020|access-date=15 June 2021|website=[[UEFA]]|language=en}}</ref> During the [[goal celebration]], he was accused of using [[Shqiptar#Use in South Slavic languages|racist slurs]] against [[Ezgjan Alioski]] and [[Egzon Bejtulai]] from the rival team, who are both [[Albanians in North Macedonia|Macedonian Albanians]]. Afterwards, he apologized for his words but denied his language was racist.<ref name="NMcelebration">{{cite web|title=Marko Arnautovic: Austria forward apologises for celebration against North Macedonia but denies using racist language|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12332512/marko-arnautovic-austria-forward-apologises-for-celebration-against-north-macedonia-but-denies-using-racist-language|website=skysports.com|date=15 June 2021|access-date=9 August 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=14 June 2021|title="Të q… nënën tënde shqiptare"/ Arnautovic flet pas ofendimit që ia bëri lojtarëve shqiptarë|url=https://www.botasot.info/futboll-sporti/1606954/te-q-hellip-nenen-tende-shqiptare-arnautovic-flet-pas-ofendimit-qe-ia-beri-lojtareve-shqiptare/|access-date=15 June 2021|website=Bota Sot|language=Albanian}}</ref> [[UEFA]] later announced an investigation into Arnautović's actions.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57472809 |title = Marko Arnautovic: Uefa to investigate incident in Austria win over North Macedonia | website = BBC Sport | date = 15 June 2021 | access-date = 17 June 2021}}</ref> He was banned by UEFA for one game for "insulting another player", resulting in him missing Austria's next game in Euro 2020 against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/33864/12333996/marko-arnautovic-banned-for-one-match-for-insulting-player-in-austrias-win-over-north-macedonia|title=Marko Arnautovic banned for one match for insulting player in Austria's win over North Macedonia|website=Sky Sports|date=16 June 2021|access-date=9 August 2022}}</ref> UEFA did not find the language to be discriminatory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57499915|title=Marko Arnautovic: Uefa suspend Austria forward for insulting North Macedonia player|website=BBC Sport|date=16 June 2021|access-date=9 August 2022}}</ref>

On 6 June 2022, he played his 100th match for Austria in a 2–1 defeat against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in the [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/0276-15537d497f87-176654104da7-1000--report-denmark-win-late-in-austria/ |title=Austria 1-2 Denmark: Late winner gives Danes victory |website=UEFA |date=6 June 2022 }}</ref> Later that year, on 25 September, he became the most-capped Austrian player with 104 caps, breaking previous record of [[Andreas Herzog]], in a 3–1 home defeat against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] during the same tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sports/croatia-seal-nations-league-semi-final-place-with-win-in-austria-idUSKBN2QQ0G4/ |title=Croatia seal Nations League semi-final place with win in Austria |publisher=Reuters |date=25 September 2022 }}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2024 |title=Nationalteam-Kader für UEFA EURO 2024 fixiert |trans-title=Final national team squad for UEFA EURO 2024 |url=https://www.oefb.at/oefb/News/OeFB-Kader-UEFA-EURO-2024 |language=de |publisher=[[Austrian Football Association]] |access-date=7 June 2024}}</ref> On 21 June, he scored a penalty, captaining his team in a 3–1 victory over [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Long |first=Dan |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13154949/euro-2024-poland-1-3-austria-marko-arnautovic-penalty-helps-ralf-rangnicks-side-to-first-win |title=Euro 2024 - Poland 1-3 Austria: Marko Arnautovic penalty helps Ralf Rangnick's side to first win |publisher=Sky Sports |date=21 June 2024 }}</ref> On 9 October 2025, he scored four goals in a 10–0 victory over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]], becoming Austria's all-time leading scorer with 45 goals, surpassing the previous record held by [[Toni Polster]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysportaustria.at/neuer-oefb-rekordtorschuetze-arnautovic-ueberholt-legende-polster/ |title=Neuer ÖFB-Rekordtorschütze! Arnautovic überholt Legende Polster |publisher=Sky Sport Austria |language=de |date=9 October 2025 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Possessing a powerful physique and good technique, Arnautović is known for his ability to hold up the ball with his back to goal and bring his teammates into play with his link-up play.<ref name="BROne">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2817795-marko-arnautovic-contract-extension-confirmed-by-west-ham-united |title=Marko Arnautovic Contract Extension Confirmed by West Ham United |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Dudko |first1=James |date=26 January 2019 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref><ref name="BRTwo">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2807375-manuel-pellegrini-cools-marko-arnautovic-exit-talk-amid-chelsea-rumours |title=Manuel Pellegrini Cools Marko Arnautovic Exit Talk Amid Chelsea Rumours |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Dudko |first1=James |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref><ref name="FourFourTwo">{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-west-ham-should-happily-wave-marko-arnautovic-goodbye-if-he-wants-leave |title=Why West Ham should happily wave Marko Arnautovic goodbye if he wants to leave |publisher=fourfourtwo.com |date=17 January 2019 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref> Despite his size, he also possesses significant pace and stamina, and is known for his ability to exploit spaces with his runs or run at opponents with the ball,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37508525/tottenham-looked-tired-loss-west-ham-ahead-ajax-ucl-clash |title=Tottenham looked tired in loss to West Ham ahead of Ajax clash |work=ESPN.com |date=27 April 2019 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref><ref name="Goal.comProfile">{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/184/player-profile/2009/08/06/1321458/goalcom-profile-marko-arnautovic |title=Goal.com Profile: Marko Arnautovic |publisher=www.goal.com |date=6 August 2009 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref> while his height helps him to win aerial challenges.<ref name="Goal.comProfile"/> A versatile forward, Arnautović has played in several offensive positions: for the majority of his career, he served as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]]; however, during the [[2017–18 West Ham United F.C. season|2017–18 season]],<ref name="2017/18">{{Soccerbase season|id=49593|season=2017|access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref> his West Ham manager [[David Moyes]] made the decision to transition the Austrian effectively into a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] or a [[centre-forward]], in order to utilise his physical and technical abilities in central areas of the pitch.<ref name="BROne"/><ref name="FourFourTwo"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6254783-former-chelsea-striker-insists-that-marko-arnautovic-would-be-a-perfect-signing-for-the-blues |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224151615/https://www.90min.com/posts/6254783-former-chelsea-striker-insists-that-marko-arnautovic-would-be-a-perfect-signing-for-the-blues |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 December 2018 |title=Former Chelsea Striker Insists That Marko Arnautovic Would be a 'Perfect Signing' for the Blues |publisher=90min.com |date=23 December 2018 |access-date=27 June 2021 }}</ref> Despite his playing ability, however, he was also a temperamental player, who was involved in several controversial incidents throughout his career.<ref name="redCard"/><ref name="NMcelebration"/><ref name="BROne"/> His skills and playing style have led him to be compared to Swedish striker [[Zlatan Ibrahimović]] in the media.<ref name="Goal.comProfile"/>

